@dsebastiantello Finally, it may be ok to use reports from other journals even if the journal doesn't have an official policy; depending on journals etc., it may be okay to reach out to editor for advice, they may expedite the process.
@dsebastiantello Err on the side of citing generously, good to acknowledge papers that influenced you (even if not in your field).
@dsebastiantello 7) "Pending recommendation" can mean editor is waiting for another report, stay patient.
@dsebastiantello 6) Be a good referee, editors can see your history (including if you were late etc). Also, it's ok to say no to a referee request but do so quickly and suggest 3 others.
@dsebastiantello 5) Don't fight desk rejections, usually a lot of thought went into it and quibbles are unlikely to be successful.
@dsebastiantello 4) Consider faster outlets at some point, getting work out is also important.
@dsebastiantello 3) as a referee, don't put recommendation in report; give comments and allow editor flexibility.
@dsebastiantello 3) spend lots of time on intro and conclusion, these are read first. Have a friend/family member read intro to make sure they can understand importance of question.
@dsebastiantello 2) adjust priors after rejections, target papers accordingly.

@dsebastiantello Oh gosh, I was using a new Twitter platform from the Uber and accidentally deleted my thread! I'm so embarrassed, but here is what I remember (probably more succinct too): 1) be careful with formatting/proofreading, mistakes are prevalent and frustrate editors.
@dsebastiantello Okay, I've got to run. I am sure I didn't do the thread thing correctly but I hope the snippets were helpful! :D
@dsebastiantello Logistics: check spam folder frequently! Seems that referee requests get sent there more than before.

@dsebastiantello Caveat: as assistant professor, probably shouldn't reject requests to referee (unless very left field). In particular, editors see reviewer history for the corresponding author. They see if you were late, etc.
@dsebastiantello For referee reports: don't put recommendation in it, this gives editor flexibility.
@dsebastiantello Best way to turn down a reviewer request is to do it fast and suggest 3 other people, it's ok to do this if you need.
@dsebastiantello "Pending recommendation" doesn't mean the editor is sitting on the paper, he/she may be waiting for an additional reviewer. Best to be patient.
@dsebastiantello Update priors after getting rejections and target papers accordingly. E.g., don't try all top 5 journals, can cost a lot of time.
@dsebastiantello I should note, panel has range of backgrounds they are drawing on: e.g., JPAM, JEBO, Southern Economic Journal, Econometrica.
@dsebastiantello Accept desk rejections when you get them, trust the editor's judgment. Some people try to fight, generally not productive.
@dsebastiantello Desk rejections common if contribution is incremental, e.g., same question but in a new country's setting. Try to match contribution with journal target.
@dsebastiantello Don't undercite; good to be friendly to literature and be honest in citing in all ideas, err on side of overciting.
@dsebastiantello Make sure formatting is thoughtful and careful, surprisingly prevalent problem.

@dsebastiantello Next: writing is very important, have a friend/family member read the introduction, they should especially be able to identify importance of idea (and catch typos!). Writing intro and conclusion should take as much time as rest of paper, these are read first.
